result.execSummary:
The defendant Robert D Purkapile was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Cause Injury while Operating with PAC (1st)(PAC>=0.15), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(2)(a)2.
  • Vehicle Owner's Liability for Failing to Stop at Scene of Accident - Hit and Run. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

3:09 Defendant Robert D Purkapile in court with attorney John T. Stichert.  Derek Dominguez appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty Dominguez presents argument regarding previous convictions of Craig Nutter and believes 2 is the appropriate number if they go back only 10 years.  Atty Stichert presents argument regarding the nature of the crimes prior to 10 years.  Court rules that the number should be 4, the theft and the 3 last disorderly conducts.  Answer to be 4 when asked about the number of crimes.

Sari Goodness is sworn as a witness.  Testifies to her employment with Marshfield Police Dept.  Testifies to receiving a report of a pedestrian accident via dispatch on 11/7/14.  Testifies to her observations upon arriving at the scene.  Spoke with lady at scene that indicated who hit the pedestrian.  Testifies to pursuing the vehicle that was indicated as hitting the pedestrian.  Testifies to stopping and identifying the vehicle driven by Robert Purkapile.  Identifies Purkapile in the courtroom.  Testifies to contact with Purkapile and observations made.  Testifies to result of PBT.  Purkapile refused Field Sobriety Tests and was then placed under arrest.  

Atty Stichert cross examines the witness.  Describes actions of the pedestrian.  Describes contact with Purkapile.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Robert D Purkapile in court with attorney John T. Stichert.  Craig Lambert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

10:27 Defendant Robert D Purkapile in court with attorney John T. Stichert.  Derek Dominguez appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Sara Goodness is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Dominguez. She is an officer with the Marshfield Police Department. On 11/7/14, she was dispatched to the scene of an accident where a pedestrian was struck by a vehicle. A witness identified the vehicle that struck the pedestrian and they pursued the vehicle. She stopped the vehicle a couple of blocks from the scene of the accident. The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom. Defendant would not make eye contact with her and he seemed tense. Defendant acknowledged that he hit a pedestrian. Defendant initially denied that he had been drinking. She transported defendant to St. Joseph's Hospital for blood draw. Results were .229. There were two dents on the top of the hood of defendant's truck and a crack with clothing fibers stuck in it. When she searched the vehicle, she found a bottle of vodka in a grocery bag and a can of beer. There was blood on the bag, which she believed to be defendant's. Testifies as to the injuries victim received from the accident. Attorney Stichert cross-examines witness. 
Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed and the defendant committed it. Bond is continued.  Arraignment scheduled for March 9, 2015 at 09:00 am.
Preliminary hearing and Arraignment on February 24, 2015 at 10:30 am.
